    <text xmlns:tei="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">
        <body>
            <head>228. Memorandum From the Special Assistant to the Deputy Secretary of State
                    <persName corresp="rec8v6444Xqn7YB4U">Whitehead</persName> (<persName
                    corresp="recoqpx2aNuHTDUHK">Timbie</persName>) to Secretary of State <persName
                    corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">Shultz</persName>
                <note n="1" place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d228fn1">Source: Department of State,
                    Bureau of Arms Control and Disarmament, Lot 01D127, 1969–1990 Subject Records of
                    James P. <persName corresp="recoqpx2aNuHTDUHK">Timbie</persName>, Box 1, <gloss
                        target="#t_START_1">
                        <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                    </gloss>/<gloss target="#t_INF_1">INF</gloss> 1987. Secret. Drafted by <persName
                        corresp="recoqpx2aNuHTDUHK">Timbie</persName>; cleared by <persName
                        corresp="recZmD7Wil34KIjtu">Nitze</persName>, <persName
                        corresp="rectgy2hXleek4j6N">Kampelman</persName>, and <persName
                        corresp="rec64QSJX0W5JIiJP">Harrison</persName>. A stamped notation
                    indicates <persName corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">Shultz</persName> saw the
                    memorandum.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1987-11-19"
                        >November 19, 1987</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <list type="subject">
                <head>SUBJECT</head>
                <item>
                    <orgName corresp="rec7JKzsWH5H30emC">NSPG</orgName> Meeting on <gloss
                        target="#t_START_1">
                        <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                    </gloss> and <rs type="event" corresp="rec0rc9kDG6TIF88N">Defense and Space</rs>
                </item>
            </list>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">
                <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss>
            </p>
            <p>Our strategy in Moscow was to focus Soviet attention on the 4800 <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04">ballistic missile</rs>
                <gloss target="#t_RV_1">RV</gloss> limit, and suggest that 6000, 4800, 1540 and the
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recTaee7UxoGjTDrc">counting rule</rs> comprise an
                acceptable package. We don’t have a formal response to this approach. Our delegation
                in Geneva continues to emphasize all of our proposed <rs corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19"
                    type="topic">sublimits</rs> (including 3300 and 1650). The Soviets probably
                perceive mixed signals here, and our primary objective is to get Soviet attention
                fixed on the 4800 as our priority need and try to settle on the above package.</p>
            <p>The <orgName corresp="recQIhKwYh3Y2wnlu">Support Group</orgName> has produced a long
                    paper<note n="2" place="foot" xml:id="d228fn2">See Tab B, <ref target="#d227"
                        >Document 227</ref>.</note> covering a large number of <gloss
                    target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> issues. Talking points follow on each issue in the paper.</p>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">
                <rs corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19" type="topic">Sublimits</rs>
            </p>
            <p>—We have the basis for a good agreement: 6000 total <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs>, 1600 launchers and bombers, 1540
                heavy <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBM</rs>
                </gloss>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs>, <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recTaee7UxoGjTDrc">counting rule</rs>.</p>
            <p>—The most important element we need to add is the 4800 <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04">ballistic missile</rs> warhead limit.</p>
            <quote>
                <p>—What we have been pushing for since <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                        <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                    </gloss> began in 1982.</p>
                <p>—Would ensure equality in this key measure of strategic capability.</p>
                <p>—Would give us headway for a substantial <rs type="topic"
                        corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">bomber</rs> and <gloss target="#t_ALCM_1">
                        <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCM</rs>
                    </gloss> force, and at the same time maintain equality with the Soviets in
                    missile <rs type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs>.</p>
            </quote>
            <p>—<gloss target="#t_JCS_1">
                    <orgName corresp="recYt5V8hImTp3Aah">JCS</orgName>
                </gloss> says this is top priority, we agree with that assessment.</p>
            <p>—Should press Soviets hard on the 4800, insist on a response. Their proposal for
                separate low limits on each component of the <rs corresp="rechRXFB0v2ifZPIR"
                    type="compound-subject">triad</rs> is out of the question. Need to get them to
                respond to our approach.</p>
            <pb facs="1014" n="987" xml:id="pg_987"/>
            <p>—3300 <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBM</rs>
                </gloss>
                <gloss target="#t_RV_1">RV</gloss>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19">sublimit</rs> would be good to have,
                but is less important to us. Low on the <gloss target="#t_JCS_1">
                    <orgName corresp="recYt5V8hImTp3Aah">JCS</orgName>
                </gloss> priority list.</p>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">Mobile <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                </gloss>
            </p>
            <p>—As we reduce, survivability of our remaining forces becomes even more important.</p>
            <p>—For <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                </gloss>, this means mobility.</p>
            <p>—We have two programs, and we will need them.</p>
            <p>—Soviets have mobile <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                </gloss>, and will want to keep them.</p>
            <p>—Problem here is <rs corresp="recvMEtDFpnXkyj45" type="topic">verification</rs>.</p>
            <p>—Verification is very difficult, but the Soviets are not going to give up their
                SS–24’s and <rs type="topic" corresp="recMS3hu34UIPBB1l">SS–25</rs>’s. Is this a
                treaty breaker, or is the real problem our unfamiliarity with verifying mobiles? We
                should work hard on <rs corresp="recvMEtDFpnXkyj45" type="topic">verification</rs>.
                Get the Soviets to work hard on it too.</p>
            <p>—When the time comes to shift our position on mobile <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                </gloss>, we should do so only in return for the <rs corresp="recvMEtDFpnXkyj45"
                    type="topic">verification</rs> provisions we need, including a low limit like
                500–1000 <rs type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs> on mobile <gloss
                    target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                </gloss>.</p>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">
                <gloss target="#t_SLCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="recRMohN3AY0ch5I7" type="topic">SLCMs</rs>
                </gloss>
            </p>
            <p>—In the end, we can go back to the idea we suggested at <rs type="event"
                    corresp="recY5TBKXKBIuAnWc">Reykjavik</rs>—an exchange of unilateral
                declarations on <gloss target="#t_SLCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="recRMohN3AY0ch5I7" type="topic">SLCM</rs>
                </gloss> plans.</p>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">Heavy <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBM</rs>
                </gloss>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recbm2CDfl6YlSCnq">Modernization</rs>
            </p>
            <p>—Soviets complain that we permit 1540 heavy <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBM</rs>
                </gloss>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs>, but they really can’t
                have them under our position because heavy <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                </gloss> can’t be tested or modernized.</p>
            <p>—In the end, we will have to give ground on <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recbm2CDfl6YlSCnq">modernization</rs> and testing, but not the 1540
                limit.</p>
            <p>—[<hi rendition="simple_italic">less than 4 lines not declassified</hi>]</p>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">Reduction Period</p>
            <p>—Seven years is what the <orgName corresp="recYt5V8hImTp3Aah">Chiefs</orgName> say
                they need.</p>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">
                <rs corresp="recbybjw3iHkqwwou" type="topic">Backfire</rs>
            </p>
            <p>—Our intelligence says this aircraft has a theater rather than intercontinental
                mission.</p>
            <p>—We know more about this aircraft now than we did 10 years ago.</p>
            <p>—The Soviets are not going to agree to count it as if it were an intercontinental
                bomber, so we will need to do something else.</p>
            <p>—We should, however, get some handle on <rs corresp="recbybjw3iHkqwwou" type="topic"
                    >Backfire</rs>. We could get a commitment on the total number, and on the
                absence of refueling capability and training.</p>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">
                <rs type="topic" corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF">Throwweight</rs>
            </p>
            <p>—The Soviets have agreed that one effect of the reductions will be to reduce their
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF">throwweight</rs> by 50%.</p>
            <pb facs="1015" n="988" xml:id="pg_988"/>
            <p>—Now we need to find a way to record this.</p>
            <p>—There are several ways to do this, all binding on the Soviets. With a little
                ingenuity, we can try to capture this important constraint.</p>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">
                <rs type="event" corresp="rec0rc9kDG6TIF88N">Defense and Space</rs>
            </p>
            <p>The <rs type="event" corresp="rec0rc9kDG6TIF88N">Defense and Space</rs> paper<note
                    n="3" place="foot" xml:id="d228fn3">See Tab A, <ref target="#d227">Document
                        227</ref>.</note> produced by the <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">
                    <orgName corresp="recft7WGb7Fww0wma">NSC</orgName>
                </gloss> staff has wildly divergent options. <gloss target="#t_OSD_1">
                    <orgName corresp="recoMngX7uLPacWDx">OSD</orgName>
                </gloss> is apparently proposing that we hold to our current position in the
                negotiations and have the President declare our intention to deploy a Phase I <gloss
                    target="#t_SDI_1">
                    <rs type="program" corresp="recVUMTljdyxyuZz3">SDI</rs>
                </gloss> system as soon as possible. Hank <persName corresp="recqtsTe4v2Qi1vTV"
                    >Cooper</persName> apparently recommends that we terminate the radar constraints
                of the <gloss target="#t_ABM_1">ABM</gloss>
                <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recKv8RyteDQ8sLn9">Treaty</rs> in order to
                permit testing and deployment of advanced US satellite sensors; this would also
                resolve the <placeName corresp="recZn2IYQQXg4H5Gm">Krasnoyarsk</placeName>
                problem.</p>
            <p>The option <orgName corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">State</orgName> has inserted in the
                paper is more modest:</p>
            <quote>
                <p>—<rs type="compound-subject" corresp="recXrGW53dEgm0PM4">Non-withdrawal</rs>
                    through 1996 (a two year extension beyond our current proposal, a year has
                    passed since <rs type="event" corresp="recY5TBKXKBIuAnWc">Reykjavik</rs>).</p>
                <p>—A period of negotiation in the years leading up to 1996 on the situation after
                    the expiration of the <rs type="compound-subject" corresp="recXrGW53dEgm0PM4"
                        >non-withdrawal</rs> commitment.</p>
                <p>—Either side could withdraw from the <gloss target="#t_ABM_1">ABM</gloss>
                    <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recKv8RyteDQ8sLn9">Treaty</rs> after
                    1996 upon six-month’s notice.</p>
            </quote>
            <p>The basic objective is to settle on a length of time for the <rs
                    type="compound-subject" corresp="recXrGW53dEgm0PM4">non-withdrawal</rs>
                commitment, and put off all other issues for subsequent negotiations. Such a minimal
                agreement may permit the <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recHoFOsQcM4e5M4k">reductions</rs> to go forward, without
                prejudice to either side’s positions on interpretation of the <gloss
                    target="#t_ABM_1">ABM</gloss>
                <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recKv8RyteDQ8sLn9">Treaty</rs> or what may
                happen after 1996.</p>
            <p>—Good beginning in <rs type="event" corresp="recY5TBKXKBIuAnWc">Reykjavik</rs>.</p>
            <p>—Agreed on the concept of a period of <rs type="compound-subject"
                    corresp="recXrGW53dEgm0PM4">non-withdrawal</rs>. Differ on the duration of this
                period. Soviets have hinted flexibility here. This probably can be resolved.</p>
            <p>—Major differences on other questions, such as what happens after this period, and
                what the <gloss target="#t_ABM_1">ABM</gloss>
                <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recKv8RyteDQ8sLn9">Treaty</rs> permits and
                prohibits.</p>
            <p>—Probably not necessary to solve all these problems in order to have a <gloss
                    target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> agreement.</p>
            <p>—A simple <rs type="compound-subject" corresp="recXrGW53dEgm0PM4">non-withdrawal</rs>
                commitment without a lot of other elaborate provisions may be all we need.</p>
            <p>—The <orgName corresp="recmLoDjMiF4yt3cM">Congress</orgName> would probably be
                careful in approving funds for <gloss target="#t_SDI_1">
                    <rs type="program" corresp="recVUMTljdyxyuZz3">SDI</rs>
                </gloss> testing to avoid jeopardizing the reductions. But they are doing that
                anyway.</p>
            <pb facs="1016" n="989" xml:id="pg_989"/>
            <p>—Success in achieving a reductions agreement would be a big plus for the <gloss
                    target="#t_SDI_1">
                    <rs type="program" corresp="recVUMTljdyxyuZz3">SDI</rs>
                </gloss> program. The best thing we could do for <gloss target="#t_SDI_1">
                    <rs type="program" corresp="recVUMTljdyxyuZz3">SDI</rs>
                </gloss> is to make it part of a strategy that pays off in deep <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recHoFOsQcM4e5M4k">reductions in strategic forces</rs>.</p>
            <p>—This would broaden support for <rs type="program" corresp="recVUMTljdyxyuZz3">the
                    program</rs>, and bound the threat <gloss target="#t_SDI_1">
                    <rs type="program" corresp="recVUMTljdyxyuZz3">SDI</rs>
                </gloss> needs to counter.</p>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">Declaration of Decision to Deploy Phase I <gloss
                    target="#t_SDI_1">
                    <rs type="program" corresp="recVUMTljdyxyuZz3">SDI</rs>
                </gloss>
            </p>
            <p>—Premature.</p>
            <p>—Don’t yet know how to meet the criteria we have established.</p>
            <p>—Would please only those in <orgName corresp="recmLoDjMiF4yt3cM">Congress</orgName>
                who are already enthusiasts, but would further shrink the base of support in
                    <orgName corresp="recmLoDjMiF4yt3cM">Congress</orgName> for <gloss
                    target="#t_SDI_1">
                    <rs type="program" corresp="recVUMTljdyxyuZz3">SDI</rs>
                </gloss>.</p>
            <p>—Won’t help get <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> reductions.</p>
            <p>—Soviets may be in a position to deploy first.</p>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">Terminate <gloss target="#t_ABM_1">ABM</gloss>
                <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recKv8RyteDQ8sLn9">Treaty</rs> Provisions
                on Radars and Other Sensors</p>
            <p>—[<hi rendition="simple_italic">less than 4 lines not declassified</hi>]</p>
            <p>—Not a good way to resolve <placeName corresp="recZn2IYQQXg4H5Gm"
                    >Krasnoyarsk</placeName>. Especially now that the Soviets say they are
                suspending construction.</p>
        </body>
    </text>
